SIMPLE: provision
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Provision
<hw>Pro*vi"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>provisio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>provision</ets>. See
<er>Provide</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of providing, or
making previous preparation.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is provided or prepared; that which is
brought together or arranged in advance; measures taken beforehand;
preparation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Making <qex>provision</qex> for the relief of strangers.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Especially, a stock of food; any kind of eatables
collected or stored; -- often in the plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And of <qex>provisions</qex> laid in large,⟦br⟧
For man and beast.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That which is stipulated in advance; a condition; a
previous agreement; a proviso; <as>as, the <ex>provisions</ex> of a
contract; the statute has many <ex>provisions</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>A canonical term for regular
induction into a benefice, comprehending nomination, collation, and
installation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Eng. Hist.)</fld> <def>A nomination by the pope to
a benefice before it became vacant, depriving the patron of his right of
presentation.</def> <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Provision</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Provision
<hw>Pro*vi"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Provisioned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Provisioning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To supply with
food; to victual; <as>as, to <ex>provision</ex> a
garrison</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They were <qex>provisioned</qex> for a journey.</q>
<rj><qau>Palfrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Provisional</ent>⟦br⟧
